<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900712-0028</DOCNO><DOCID>900712-0028.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   Business and Finance</HL><DATE>07/12/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   THE U.S. WON assurances from six nations and the EC thatthey will agree to cut farm subsidies. But some Europeans atthe economic summit claimed victory because the understandingdoesn't call for the elimination of export subsidies, andU.S. aides said tough talks lie ahead. Meanwhile, the summitleaders agreed to follow different paths on the environmentand aid to the Soviets.   ---</LP><TEXT>   U.S. banks were ordered to write off 20% of their $11.1billion in loans to Brazil and an additional 20% of their$2.9 billion in Argentine portfolios. The action could forcesome banks, especially Citicorp, to boost reserves.   ---   Stock prices rose sharply on positive second-quarterearnings and on bullish news for oil companies. The Dow JonesIndustrial Average jumped 41.83 points to 2932.67. The dollargained and bonds were flat.   ---   Wall Street bond dealers deluged the Treasury with whatamounted to bogus bids for seven-year notes to retaliate fora change in auction rules.   ---   Five oil ministers from the Persian Gulf urged OPEC tofreeze its output ceiling to try to raise its average crudeprice to at least $18 a barrel. Oil prices gained on thenews, as did the shares of U.S. oil companies.   ---   A grand jury indicted Edwin T. McBirney III, former ownerof defunct Sunbelt Savings, in the second big indictment byU.S. thrift-fraud prosecutors in the past month.   ---   Five senators violated ethics rules in the Sandamp;L scandal, acitizens group argued. Meanwhile, Bush voiced confidence inthe integrity of his son, who faces a thrift-related probe.   ---   PS New Mexico was approached by a small venture-capitalfirm about acquiring the utility. The move may flush outother interested buyers. PS New Mexico's stock rose $2 to$11.75.   ---   The first factory for making computer chips withsuperconducting materials is to be unveiled today byConductus, a tiny Silicon Valley firm.   ---   Banks would be required to adhere to securitiesregulations if they market investment trusts to compete withmutual funds, the SEC announced.   ---   First Executive is seeking to keep secret the fullcontents of a consulting report that the insurer said provedits financial strength and viability.   ---   CBS Inc. posted a 16% increase in second-quarter profit.But the company said the prospect for continued growth thisyear is &quot;uncertain.&quot;   ---   The Chicago Merc will allow two traders convicted Mondayon federal felony charges to keep trading for their ownaccounts pending a hearing.   ---   Most U.S. voters believe Bush is breaking his no-taxpledge, but they don't much blame him for it and are resignedto a tax increase, according to a Wall Street Journal/NBCpoll.   ---   Hartmarx halved its dividend and took a $51 millionafter-tax charge. A sales slump has hurt the clothing firm.   ---   Markets --   Stocks: Volume 162,220,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials2932.67, up 41.83; transportation 1155.29, up 9.67; utilities204.79, up 1.19.   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3410.30, off0.73.   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 131.36, up 0.70; spotindex 132.46, up 0.35.   Dollar: 148.50 yen, up 0.20; 1.6560 marks, up 0.0135.</TEXT></DOC>